## New rules, added based on command usage experience:

### Heading capitalization
- All headings (H1, H2, H3, etc.) should start with a capital letter, but the rest of the words should use lowercase letters (sentence case)
- Example: "What is Enyu and why it mattered" (not "What Is Enyu and Why It Mattered")
- Exception: Proper nouns, acronyms, and brand names should maintain their standard capitalization

### Preferred LinkedIn hashtags
When creating LinkedIn posts, prefer these hashtags (list will be updated with each command usage):
- frontend
- composable
- composableCX
- CustomerPortal
- SelfService

### Core positioning repetition
- You do not need to restate "O2S is an open-source composable frontend framework for customer self-service portals" in every single piece of content.
- Use the full positioning statement when it helps new readers understand what O2S is; for feature or integration announcements, focus mainly on the specific change and its impact.

### LinkedIn narrative patterns
- LinkedIn posts do not always need an explicit "problem ‚Üí solution" structure.
- For feature and release announcements, it is perfectly fine to focus only on what is new and why it is useful (benefits, impact, who it helps).
- Reserve the problem/solution framing mainly for educational or thought-leadership posts where it adds clarity.

### Architecture wording in public content
- Do not call external systems (e.g., Contentful, Zendesk) "adapters".
- When you need to mention adapters, refer to the **O2S integration** as the adapter, e.g. "the Contentful integration acts as a CMS adapter behind O2S".
